# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# .git-blame-ignore-revs – revisions `git blame` should skip.
#
# `git blame` walks the history of a file line by line. Big-bang
# refactors (a project-wide re-format, a license header pass, a
# tooling migration) touch almost every line in the repository and
# drown the actual authorship signal in noise. The standard remedy
# is to list those revisions here and configure git to consult the
# file:
#
#   git config blame.ignoreRevsFile .git-blame-ignore-revs
#
# Modern versions of `git` (>= 2.23) honour the file automatically
# when it lives at the repository root, so no per-developer setup
# is required.
#
# Conventions:
#   * One full SHA per line.
#   * Lines starting with `#` are comments and are ignored.
#   * New entries must be added *after* a format / migration commit
#     lands on the branch; pre-emptively adding future SHAs is a
#     footgun (rebase rewrites them).
